                    },
                    "message": {
                        "S": "\n\n\n\nMark Waterice: Well, Jim, I understand your frustration, but I have to respectfully disagree. While it's true that you don't need a blood sample to draft a running back, it's not as simple as just picking a guy who can run fast and hit hard. There's a lot more that goes into it than that.\n\nFor one, you need to consider the player's durability. Can he withstand the physical toll of carrying the ball 20-30 times a game? Can he stay healthy throughout the season? That's a big concern, especially when you're talking about a player's long-term potential.\n\nSecondly, you need to look at the player's vision and instincts."
                    },
                    "message_in_thread": {
                        "N": "3"
